: nickname for someone with white hair or a remarkably pale complexion, from Middle Low German <i>witte</i> ‘white’.","South German: from a short form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Wittigo</i>. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine).","English (Hampshire and Wiltshire): variant of   White  ."],"variants":[{"name":"White","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>white</i>, <i>wit</i> (Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’), hence a nickname for someone with white hair or a pale complexion. In some cases it is perhaps from a Middle English survival of the Old English personal name <i>Hwīta</i>, a short form of names in <i>Hwīt-</i> (from <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’). The name may also be topographic, referring to someone who lived by a bend or curve in a river or road (from Old English <i>wiht</i> ‘bend’), the source of the placename of Great Whyte in Ramsey, Huntingdonshire (compare   Wight  ). This name is also a variant of   Wight  . The surname <i>White</i> is also very common among African Americans.","Irish and Scottish: adopted for any of several Irish and Scottish Gaelic names based on <i>bán</i> ‘white, fair’ (see   Bain   1,   McElwain  ) or <i>fionn</i> ‘fair’ (see   Finn   1). The English surname has been Gaelicized in Ireland as <b>de Faoite</b>.","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘white’, for example German   Weiss  , French   Blanc  , Polish <b>Białas</b> (see   Bialas  ), Slovenian   Belec  , or any other synonymous Slavic surname beginning with <i>Bel-</i>, <i>Bev-</i>, <i>Biel-</i> or <i>Bil-</i>."]},{"name":"Witte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Franz, Kurt, Erwin, Gerhard, Dieter, Egon, Fritz, Gerhart, Lorenz, Eldor, Erhart.","German: variant of   Witt  .","Dutch: nickname for someone with white or blonde hair or an unusually pale complexion, from Middle Dutch <i>witte</i> ‘white’. Compare   De Witte  ."]},{"name":"Witts","meanings":["English: variant of   Witt  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Americanized form of German   Witz   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":45,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":54,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Auctina Witt was born in 1170, in Raby, Cheshire, England as the daughter of Nevil Witt De Raby and Mrs Nevil Witt De Raby. She married Richard De Norville II in 1199, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1230, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1170–1230":"1170–1230","1164–1200":"1164–1200","1200–1260":"1200–1260","1150–1240":"1150–1240","–Female":"Surnud","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1199":"1199","1230":"1230","1164":"1164","1240":"1240","before 1170":"enne 1170","1150":"1150","1260":"1260","1170":"1170","Raby, Cheshire, England":"Raby, Cheshire, England","England":"England","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, England","Norville, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Norville, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1170–1230":"1170–1230","1164–1200":"1164–1200","1200–1260":"1200–1260","1150–1240":"1150–1240","–Female":"Kuollut","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1199":"1199","1230":"1230","1164":"1164","1240":"1240","before 1170":"ennen vuott